Task 1¶

Subtask 1: Training XGBoost¶

For my experiments, I used the Magic Telescope dataset, which is used to classify whether gamma radiation has been detected, based on advanced measurements. All variables in this dataset are continuous.

On this data, I trained an XGBoost model with 100 estimators and a maximum depth of 3. Before training, I divided the set into training and test sets to then evaluate the model. I obtained an accuracy of 0.8723 and an AUC of 0.9318.

Subtask 2: Calculate predictions¶

I chose two observations, the first positive and the second negative, to see how the model would behave. Below I show the observations I selected.

Out[11]:
fLength: fWidth: fSize: fConc: fConc1: fAsym: fM3Long: fM3Trans: fAlpha: fDist:
0 28.7967 16.0021 2.6449 0.3918 0.1982 27.7004 22.0110 -8.2027 40.092 81.8828
19019 187.1814 53.0014 3.2093 0.2876 0.1539 -167.3125 -168.4558 31.4755 52.731 272.3174

The model classified both cases correctly, for the first I got a prediction of 0.816 and for the second I got a prediction of 0.0006.

Subtask 3: Calculate the decomposition of predictions¶

After calculating the Shapley value, we can see which variables had the greatest impact on the difference between the prediction for a given observation and the expected value over the entire set. The positive prediction of the first observation was influenced by the variables fLength and fWidth. The negative prediction of the second observation was influenced by almost all variables, meaning that if we take one of these measurements and paste it into the other observations the expected value of the prediction decreases.

Subtask 4: Different variables of the highest importance¶

To show what differences there might be in the influences of the variables in question, I chose observations 3 and 9, which were correctly classified as positive. In one prediction the features fSize and fConc played a key role, and in the other fAlpha and fWidth.

Subtask 5: Variable which has different attributions¶

For the first two observations, we can look at the feature fAsym, whose values are almost identical. Nevertheless, it has a positive effect on prediction in one case and a negative effect in the other.

Subtask 6: Difference between packages¶

The differences between the packages are small, but we can see them for the first observation, for example. The dalex package showed that the impact of the variable fAlpha was the highest, while the shap package only placed it 4th in terms of importance.

Subtask 7: Difference between models¶

I trained a second model, Random Forest, on the same dataset. I decided to compare the explanations for these models. It was obvious that the numerical values would change, as we have two different prediction values for two different models. The example below shows two graphs: the first for XGBoost and the second for Random Forest. We can see similarities, for example in both models the variable fAlpha played the biggest role, but there are also differences. The hierarchy of variables that contribute positively has changed.

df = pd.read_csv('MagicTelescope.csv').dropna()

X = df.drop(columns='TARGET').iloc[:,1:]
y = (df.TARGET == "g")

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=17)

    max_depth=3,
    use_label_encoder=False,
    eval_metric="logloss",
)

model.fit(X_train, y_train)
